text: I feel as if this is one of those movies where the trailer is better than the actual movie itself. While I too am admittedly skeptical, and even willing to go indulge in the cheeziness, I don't really think I'd like to find such a comical effect in a video game movie that this appears to show. What fans want to see is action, and while I sensed a few exciting tidbits here and there, the concept just comes out with an dull reveal.  At first, I was excited to see the trailer, having not seen a video game film since Disney's Wreck-It-Ralph. As a matter of fact, I personally enjoyed Wreck-It-Ralph for the unique, action packed storyline it brought to the table, truly bringing out an exciting concept towards the audience. When I finished seeing the movie, I wanted to watch it again, since I was just that excited from the first second to the ending credits. Sure, part of me could say this due to certain appearances from Sonic, Bowser, and characters in that area. However, despite originally seeing the movie for that reason, I actually fell in love with that plot, which surprised me considering certain character appearances had really urged me to go see it, rather than the initial storyline.  Who knows, I could totally prove myself wrong after seeing the movie, and find out that it's worthwhile. Yet, despite a few moments where I laughed to myself, this trailer provided me with that cheesy, unsatisfying reaction that I despise of with movies. Let's face it, the fans want to see an original and captivating twist in the specific franchises they love.  In the end, this movie could go either way, but I don't see as much success in the long run. I do have lots of high respect in the process that went behind the movie, absolutely. It seems as if the script is lacking in selling to the modern-day audience, I suppose. I'll just wait for Sony to finish up that Sonic the Hedgehog movie they mentioned back in June 2014. Hopefully then that "live action/CGI film" will provide more of a modern, action-packed experience without getting too corny.   #QOTD : Any franchises you guys would like to see made into a movie? I've overheard lots of Zelda fans wanting some love. For some reason, I'd like to see a live action film of a *crossover* between Mario and Sonic. That'd definitely be something more exciting, rather than some silly olympic games. :P

text: Oh.... my.... god.....      A trailer for a comedy starring Adam Sander....... THAT ACTUALLY MADE ME FUCKING LAUGH!!!!!!!   Okay, I should point out that I really, really hate Adam Sandler. He's an annoying, unfunny and pretentious jackass who thinks anything he puts on screen will get a laugh out of the retarded audiences. Even films like Paul Blart and Bucky Larson he didn't even star in yet I can still blame him for producing them. Happy Madison is basically the comedy equivalent to Platinum Dunes.  So far the only Adam Sandler movie I have ever sat through and genuinely enjoyed was Hotel Transylvania. Sure it's not a great animated film but I still had fun with it and I can actually tolerate Sandler's performance in that movie.... though I still do have some doubts about the sequel.  For once in my damn life, I watched a trailer for an upcoming Adam Sandler movie that is actually very funny. That last bit with the Pac-Man creator made me laugh harder than I ever did before.  Don't get me wrong, this movie can still end up like garbage just like Sandler's other movies(considering one of the writers previously wrote Grown Ups 2) but at the same time there is a small glimmer of hope that this could work.  Whether or not it'll suck I'll let the internet critics decide on this one. If it does end up getting decent reviews(which is unlikely) then I might consider giving it a chance.

text: First, in 1982, Disney gave us a glimpse of a world where a man was sucked into a video game in "Tron", and it was a hit. Then, 11 years later, in 1993, Hollywood Pictures did a live-action video game movie, "Super Mario Bros." and it flopped and was panned by critics. Nineteen years later, in 2012, Disney gave us a glimpse inside the video game universe in "Wreck-It Ralph", and it was a hit. Now, 3 years later, Columbia is giving us a glimpse of a world where video games come to life in "Pixels" because of aliens seeing it as a "War of the Worlds" threat (typical). While this movie could a hit in the box office, I predict that critics are not going to like this (probably the acting will screw it up). Plus, the director of this movie is Chris Columbus, the same guy who directed the first 2 "Home Alone" movies (my all-time favorite Christmas films), and the first 2 "Harry Potter" movies, and all 4 films were big hits with audiences. I hope he hasn't lost his touch in this film. As for Adam Sandler, I have neither a comment nor a complaint about him.

text: When teens come on here to talk about how or right-out say kids never play games with pixel graphics, or old games, today, I fucking cringe my toes. There are millions of tids who play those games today, most of them have dads or moms who played them though. It is true that they are the minority, but they are there. Also, most kids, I assure you, have played Pacman and Donkey Kong, since they're classic games. Maybe modern versions, but still. Another reason for using pixels is obviously that it's easier to animate. Also, I really don't think there's many modern characters that people have as much a connection with as Pacman, DK etc., so the Pacman scene with the creator wouldn't really make sense to me if it was Master Chief and his creator standing there. They could just have cut that out though. They did not need to make that. But what does it matter what games it is if it's a good story? Execution, guys, that is the key! They could have tried to be more relevant with newer games, but they don't have to. But we don't know if they will, since we have not seen the film yet. Maybe the aliens came and studied it without us knowing it, and created some modern CoD monsters. But I doubt it. Lastly, with the sky-rocketing popularity in old games again, with the Atari Landfill excavation, documentaries about it, the AVGN's sudden fast increase in viewers, with JonTron and Game Grumps, and all these other retro gaming channels/people who have suddenly seen a jump in popularity lately, how can one really say these games are not relevant? Hm? Food for thought :)

text: This movie looks dead on arrival. Aliens look at a couple of video games and take that as inspiration to kill us? First off, why would aliens with the technology to build these things waste all that time and resources on building those things? Second, why would they build things that we already know how to defeat? Third, why did they think him saying they were all going to die was funny?  Look, I'm willing to let a movie do some *really* outlandish things so a situation can happen, but this looks like its going to nothing but pandering to the gamer audience with nothing to deliver in terms of narrative. The production looks really good, and the actors they chose are at least competent and even good in roles like this, but.... aliens making video game characters to kills us... Sorry, my brain just says nope to that.

text: Being a fan of retro gaming I think this concept sounds good on paper, but a missed opportunity in practice. If the cast aren't taking the invasion seriously, then why should I take the film seriously? A potential concept wasted on the wrong genres. The idea of pixels in the physical world should be used for abstract, symbolising and psychological themes, not a comedy type global invasion. At least, this is how I feel.

text: Mixed feelings about this one. I really don't like Adam Sandler and the concept seems a little too close to that one episode of Futurama. There's also the thing about how many of the jokes I'll get: being born in 1994 and not playing any videogames until I got a PS2 in 1999 I'll probably only get the jokes about the most iconic games featured (Pac Man, Donkey Kong, Space Invaders etc.) for a lot of the rest of the movie I'll probably just laugh along while inwardly thinking "I've never even heard of that game." (I get that they'll bring back a lot of memories for some, just not me). However, there are some things that make it look worthwhile. Dinklage and that part at 2:02 - 2:20

text: There are several allotropes of carbon of which the best known are graphite, diamond, and amorphous carbon. The physical properties of carbon vary widely with the allotropic form. For example, graphite is opaque and black, while diamond is highly transparent. Graphite is soft enough to form a streak on paper (hence its name, from the Greek word "γράφω" which means "to write"), while diamond is the hardest naturally-occurring material known. Graphite is a very good conductor, while diamond has a very low electrical conductivity. Under normal conditions, diamond, carbon nanotubes, and graphene have the highest thermal conductivities of all known materials.

text: This is a joke trailer right? Because this just seems lazy and manipulative. Like does this trailer really look like anyone put all of their effort into it? Like this was their dream project they have been wanting to make their whole life? Or does it feel like some rich asshole trying to cash in on video game popularity and nostalgia. I did not laugh at a single moment in this trailer. Everything about it made me cringe. They are using video game character from before the 1980's so their trying to appeal to adults right? Then why at 1:12 are they explaining who the characters are?!? Every line of dialog in the trailer is cliched garbage desperately trying to get anyone to laugh. The humor is for toddlers so it will isolate the adult audience, and they are using old video game characters which isolates the younger audience. It appeals to NO ONE. Not to mention the whole idea is ripped off from a cartoon.

text: I know it's a trailer, but let me explain the many problems I found through the film's sources.  1. Why would they send a time capsule of everything about Earth? I know that it meant to find aliens and bring peace, but what justice it will do? Do you know how long it takes for a time capsule to leave the Solar System, or miles away from there? It would've taken decades to find life in space. What if the capsule gets destroyed by an asteroid field (like the one in our solar system)? What if it fell into a gas planet, or a deserted, lifeless planet, or a black hole? That time capsule would be pretty much be forgotten, drifting in space for all eternity. This is where all your taxpayer money goes, people!  2. How did the aliens even find us? Did we install coordinates to our planet so they'll find us? How would the aliens know which solar system were on?  3. How did the aliens mistake the time capsule from a "message of peace" to a declaration of war? All that information from the capsule would at least intrigued them into visiting us and NOT kill us. I mean, these aliens speak in an extraterrestrial language and don't understand our languages, let alone English. There would be a chance that these aliens would either take decades studying the damn capsule like we do for alien tech OR toss it away/eat it as a means of not giving a shit.  4. The aliens use the games from the time capsule as weapons to attack Earth. If they're capable of creating of something like that, WHY DIDN'T THEY USE THEIR OWN TECHNOLOGY?! These aliens are advanced enough to bring video game characters to life and NOT use their own arsenal?! Is this going to be like After Earth when the movie focuses on the Ursa as the main villain and not the ACTUAL aliens!?  5. and certainly the biggest: WHY ALIENS!? There's so many possibilities you could've done with this idea and you used aliens!? How uninspired are these guys!?  Through these 5 major problems, I'm not going to watch the film, but what I AM going to do is wait for their overall percentage on RottenTomatoes,com. I know people are going to say, "Dude, it's just a movie, chill," but guys! This is the company that brought us Jack and Jill and Bucky Larson: Born to be a Star!   I'm... done ranting. You can ignore my post and go watch the movie on July 24, but remember that you will not only waste your valuable time, but also killing what's left of your brain cells from the sheer lack of potential this movie will have.

text: (sigh) Adam Sandler, .....by having grown-up humor, you make it more CHILDISH. By modernizing the dialogue, you make it more DATED. And by changing the source material, you show how much you DON'T respect what's already perfect. I'm not going to act like everything video game creators wrote was a masterpiece, but when they got it right, they got it right. They don't NEED to be updated. They don't NEED to be fixed. They don't even really need to have MOVIES made about them! But if you're GOING to do it, the very least you can do is understand the source material.
author: sanslazyb101

text: They're NOT just simple kids games. They're games that we are continuing to play even today. They're games that we remember years later, even when other games fade from our memory. They're games we will never forget - and for good reason! They're games that helped shape our childhoods, through well thought-out writing, imaginative drawings and endearing morals. And the idea of this... PIXELS... shaping somebody's childhood, the fact that it even has the same name... just makes me sick to my stomach! Maybe these "simple kids games" are far more adult than you give them credit for. And I guarantee that'll show, when years later, both children and adults will still be playing these "simple kids games" while pandering bullshit like this disappears out of people's consciousness - also for good reason! Good art doesn't come from focus groups and statistics. It comes from people who share how they see things in their own unique way.

text: Oh God. Oh Adam Sandler, no. Just, You can't just make dumb jokes when people are dying in a fuckin' alien invasion. You can't not explain how damn stupid an alien race that creates 3-dimentional pixelated killing machines to... fuck it. This premise is fucking stupid, and when the premise is stupid, there's nothing to save a film, except some nice CG graphics and fancy colours to keep the lowest common denominator entertained for what? 90 minutes? Wreck-it-Ralph already did the videogame thing better. Avengers and a hundred others already did the alien invasion better. The LEGO Movie already did the blocky aesthetic thing better. And on top of this excuse-for-product-placement bullshit is Adam "I can't act and I can't make jokes but I still get work in comedy films" Sandler. No. This is just my opinion, though.

text: Man, Fuck all you pretentious douche bags who say no mixing movies and videos games, and video games are a kids thing. Videos Games are a fucking art form, just as valid if not superior to movies and TV. You waste how many hours of your life watching Game of Thrones, and Walking Dead, which contains about the same level of realism as most fantasy games, and you have the right to judge other peoples choice entertainment and call theirs a waste of time.  Video games not only give you as complex and emotional plots as movies and Shows, they also allow you to form a deeper bond with the characters because you actually play as that character. And when you loss a team mate in a game you feel the lose even more than a liked character in a movie, because you actually played alongside that character and not just observing from afar, not to mention even decisions you make in a lot of games greatly affect the outcome. Games these days ain't the shit games you old farts played on your Atari and in Arcades, that you gave up as you grew up.  Because of you pretentious douches putting this connotation on Video Games, orchestras and artists actually hesitate to play Video Game songs live. That are just as complex and artistic as movie songs and etc.

This movie looks like utter fucking garbage, and Adam Sandler doesn't even seem to be the guy that knows a lot about gaming lore so why make this trash? Mr.Sandler's gonna be walking away with a stack of cash in his pocket. I don't hate him. I thought he was a funny guy back in the day but EVERYTHING he's recently made, in my opinion (and in the majority of opinions) is just suckage. The cast looks decent (except for Sandler and Kevin James is losing his charm). I'm not trying to piss anyone off, this is my opinion, I feel sorry for Adam Sandler, I really do. There's nothing that anyone can say and nothing he can make that'll convince me that he's like his old self again. Adam, please, please, please, PLEASE stop digging a deeper grave for your career, Adam. -Sincerely, me and millions of others.

text: The end of this movie gave me a very intriguing thought..... HoloLens; Imagine the possibilities if all/every developer of every game represented in this movie, Nintendo included, collaborated with Micro$oft to make similar, re-imagined HoloLens experiences of our 8-bit classics in 3D model pixel form represented in the movie, and have them play identically represented to the movie as well. (The reason I suggest 8-bit in 3D model pixel form like the movie, would be as a simple, not heavily graphic start without drastically changing the original, simplistic game play formula(s) design, etc, and slowly moving up the ladder as time progresses) A few examples; (SPOILER ALERT!: If you haven't seen this movie yet, read at your own risk.  You've been warned.)  1: As already seen, Donkey Kong could play placing you yourself to run the ramps, leap the barrels and hammer them, climb the ladders, etc. 2: While not a major part of the movie, the ducks from Duck Hunt would simply fly free as they always have and the obvious aim and shoot.  Or imagine shooting down the aliens from Galaga. 3: Pac-Man already has a similar GameCube variation, Pac-Man Vs, similar to the "Ghost" cars scenario represented.  The 2 could be combined for 1st person viewpoint of Pac-Man, or ghosts for in a same-mannered multiplayer mode.

text: This is the FIRST time ever that i post an opinion about a film on a Youtube page. On a web page even. The film was THAT bad. Don't do it to yourself.  This is one of the SHITTIEST movies i've ever seen. SO sorry I hadn't watch the trailer beforehand and only read the plot summary (I thought Columbus would never do a movie that you would regret watching. I might have been watching it for Peter Dinklage, if I knew he would be there. Although I think he's just there for the joy of playing an unapologetic bastard). 1) Although - the trailer is a straight up lie, it's all "Independence day" vibe, though the film itself was totally "Adam Sandler" (after Hotel Transylvania I thought he is able do a good movie, but no, he's just Adam Sandler) / sitcom / characters throwing personal insults on each other (dressed up as jokes) kind of thing. 2) There wasn't even that much of sfx perks, most of the "action" revolved around the characters who SUCK (in every interpretation possible). The game things were... somewhere on the background really. 3) If you consider yourself a feminist - nothing will ever be as painful as this.   Basically - this is the wettest dream of a self-indulgent hikki nerd loser man who has never been satisfied with anything in his life and is still so full of himself that it turns out the only way anyone could be better than him is because they cheat. And I understand the power of fantasy, I know, every other time a movie is about a nobody who saves the world through some of their small personal merit, but this is just a disgrace. "He liked to slice up kittens and one day it helped him become a hero" is just one tiny step away from this film, and I personally consider the movie to be an insult to all hikkis, all the sweet nerdy guys, all the people who work hard but just so happen not to have a swanky job and maybe even to all gamers in general (think about that, there are only 3 gamer characters (not including the kid, he has no character) in the film: 1) a dingbat who is positively crazy about a girl game character and who also happens to believe all conspiracy theories that ever existed; 2) an egoistical criminal who cheats; 3) and Adam Sandler at his worst). And the depiction of the relations between men and women is just a slap on the face of any nice person ever.  I honestly don't know what was the purpose of the film. Maybe just getting money, but im not even sure of that.

text: I just got back from Pixels. What I can tell you is this: It's not good, but I didn't hate it like everyone else did. From what I've heard from every review I've read, they were pretty harsh on it.  I'd say the positives are visual effects and when the video games are attacking.  Everyone in their reviews have immaturely disregard the action sequences and the visual effects due to them being in an Adam Sandler movie. Plus there are cool cameos by a lot of 80's property.  But the negatives are it's still an Adam Sandler movie with jokes that don't work and it doesn't know what it want to be. There are times where it's tries to have kid friend moment, but then it turns into a adult joke.  I'd say your better off renting it at RedBox and skip to the action scenes.   So yeah, it's a rental.  It wasn't good, I wasn't mad like everyone else did.

text: There's clearly an audience for Adam Sandler films that regurgitate the same ideals over and over. We seem to forget that the man has starred in some really good films. Reign Over Me, The Wedding Singer and Punch Drunk Love to name a few. Sure the films that display his raw anger are memorable, but the ones that diversify Sandler's approach to acting in films are his most successful. It's just a pain that dreck sullies his decent performances more often than not. Grown Ups was acceptable, but the second film was needless, unfunny and boring. Jack & Jill....well the less said the better. Pixels is one of those films where people may need to turn their brain off to enjoy. But maybe playing Saints Row 4 covers all the lunacy this film attempts to replicate. It doesn't matter if you like this film or not, this is what Sandler wants and we'll see a lot more of it in the future because money and the never-ending slew of sophomoric ideas. One day Sandler might show us another instance of acting quality, but if the trailer is anything to go by, his most compelling days are behind him.

text: After seeing it i have to say it is not bad as so many are saying. Is it good or memorable? Of course not. It is just mediocre, popcorn, feel good and digestible retro tribute not to be taken seriously. If you are going to see this just for old Arcade characters and not Sandler then you will be pleased, because they really look good and while those scenes play out you are having fun. There were also few chuckle moments here and there plus Peter Dinklage does a great job being douchebag. Everything else, starting from the cast, screenplay, jokes, romance, plausability is not delivering and is just ADAM SANDLER cashing his check while being on another paid vacation. It is not the worst film of 2015, but it is wasted potential. 2.5/5

text: Am I the only one who doesn't give a flying shiz about how bad Adam Sandler was in this film?  The movie is a recreation the 2010 film "Pixels", and that's what I walked into the movie expecting to see. I was pretty satisfied. It's basically a poorman's Ghostbusters. The celebrity actors in this film are a bonus, so why is it that all the critics are so aimed towards them?! The movie's isn't about Adam, it's about the Chaos of Video Games Invading Our Planet! Adam's just there because a movie needs characters + Hollywood needs celebrities! They don't even mention Kevin James. Just "AdAm SaNdLeR bAD AdAm SaNdLeR bAd AdAm SaNdLeR bAd"   I definitely understand why everyone thinks it's bad, but I found the movie fun to watch because I didn't worry so much about the actors, especially in 3D.    Anyways, i meant to type this 5 years ago but forgot.
